                'description' => 'Polio is a crippling and potentially deadly infectious disease caused by a virus that invades the brain and spinal cord, causing paralysis. When you first get polio, you may feel like you have the flu. You might have a fever, sore throat, cough, headache, stomach pain, and vomiting. These symptoms usually go away in 2 to 5 days. The virus lives in an infected person’s throat and intestines. It spreads through contact with poop. You can get it if you: Touch poop that has the virus on it and then touch your mouth, Eat food or drink liquids that have the virus in them, Touch objects that have the virus on them and then touch your mouth, nose, or eyes, Have close contact with someone who has the virus — for example, by kissing the person or caring for the person when they’re sick. You can pass the virus to others for weeks. Up to 72% of people with polio don’t have any symptoms, so they may not know they’re infected. But they can still spread the virus to others.',
