                'treatment' => 'Acute hepatitis B infection doesn\'t require treatment. If you develop chronic hepatitis B, you may need treatment with antiviral medications. Antiviral medications can\'t cure hepatitis B, but they can help control the virus so that it doesn\'t damage your liver. Antiviral medications are taken orally. Chronic hepatitis B infection may eventually cause severe liver damage and liver cancer. If you have chronic hepatitis B, your doctor may recommend antiviral medications to reduce the risk of liver cancer. If your liver has been severely damaged, a liver transplant may be an option.',
                'description' => 'Hepatitis B is a serious liver infection caused by the hepatitis B virus (HBV). For some people, hepatitis B infection becomes chronic, meaning it lasts more than six months. Having chronic hepatitis B increases your risk of developing liver failure, liver cancer or cirrhosis — a condition that permanently scars of the liver. Most people infected with hepatitis B as adults recover fully, even if their signs and symptoms are severe. Infants and children are more likely to develop a chronic hepatitis B infection. A vaccine can prevent hepatitis B, but there\'s no cure if you have it. If you\'re infected, taking certain precautions can help prevent spreading HBV to others.',
