                'prevention' => 'Hepatitis A vaccination',
                'treatment' => 'There\'s no specific treatment for hepatitis A. But symptoms of acute hepatitis A infection can be treated, and most people with hepatitis A eventually recover completely with no permanent liver damage. Treatment mainly involves relieving symptoms. Your doctor may recommend: Rest. Many people with hepatitis A infection feel tired and sick and have less energy. You may need to take a break from your normal daily activities until your energy levels return to normal. Adequate nutrition. If you\'re nauseated, you may not feel like eating. However, it\'s important to get adequate nutrition. Until your appetite returns, your doctor may recommend a special diet to help promote healing and restore proper liver function. Follow your doctor\'s instructions regarding diet.',
                'description' => 'Hepatitis A is a highly contagious liver infection caused by the hepatitis A virus. The virus is one of several types of hepatitis viruses that cause inflammation and affect your liver\'s ability to function. You\'re most likely to get hepatitis A from contaminated food or water or from close contact with a person or object that\'s infected. Mild cases of hepatitis A don\'t require treatment. Most people who are infected recover completely with no permanent liver damage. Practicing good hygiene, including washing hands frequently, is one of the best ways to protect against hepatitis A. Vaccines are available for people most at risk.',
