            [
                'name' => 'Varicella (Chickenpox)',
                'symptoms' => 'Fever, Loss of appetite, Headache, Tiredness and a general feeling of being unwell (malaise), A skin rash made up of blister-like lesions, which first appear on the face and trunk, and then spread throughout the body, Itching',
                'prevention' => 'Chickenpox vaccine',
                'treatment' => 'Chickenpox is usually mild and runs its course in five to 10 days, but it can cause more serious problems when teens and adults get it. People who have weakened immune systems or other medical problems may have complications from chickenpox. They may get pneumonia or, rarely, an inflammation of the brain (encephalitis). They may need to be treated in the hospital. If you have chickenpox, you can help prevent spreading the virus to others by staying home until all blisters scab over. If you\'re at high risk of complications from chickenpox — for example, you\'re pregnant, you have a weakened immune system or you\'re an adult — your doctor may prescribe an antiviral medication. Antiviral drugs lessen the severity of chickenpox and may prevent complications. They work best if given within the first 24 hours after the rash appears. Acetaminophen (Tylenol, others) can help relieve pain and fever. Never give aspirin to children with chickenpox. It may lead to Reye\'s syndrome, a rare but life-threatening condition.',
                'description' => 'Chickenpox is a highly contagious disease caused by the varicella-zoster virus (VZV). It can cause an itchy, blister-like rash. The rash first appears on the chest, back, and face, and then spreads over the entire body, causing between 250 and 500 itchy blisters. Chickenpox can be serious, especially in babies, adults, and people with weakened immune systems. It spreads easily from infected people to others who have never had chickenpox or received the chickenpox vaccine. Chickenpox spreads in the air through coughing or sneezing. It can also be spread by touching or breathing in the virus particles that come from chickenpox blisters. A person with chickenpox can spread the disease from 1 to 2 days before they get the rash until all their chickenpox blisters have formed scabs. This usually happens within 5 to 7 days of the rash appearing.',
